// C2: Acting Components
instance HeatbedActuator : DTDFVocab:ActingComponent [
    base:desc "Resistive heating element sized 214×214×3mm capable of delivering at least 100W of thermal energy within the Styrofoam enclosure"
]

instance AirCirculationFan : DTDFVocab:ActingComponent [
    base:desc "12V/24V fan providing 0.02 m³/s airflow rate for uniform temperature distribution within the incubator enclosure"
]

// C3: Physical Sensing Components
instance InternalTemperatureSensor : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "DS18S20 digital temperature sensor measuring internal thermal conditions with ±0.5°C accuracy (-55°C to +125°C range)"
    DTDFVocab:producedData InternalTemperatureDataTransmitted
]

instance ExternalTemperatureSensor : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "DS18S20 digital temperature sensor measuring external thermal conditions with ±0.5°C accuracy (-55°C to +125°C range)"
    DTDFVocab:producedData ExternalTemperatureDataTransmitted
]

// C4: Physical-to-Virtual Interaction
instance InternalTemperatureDataTransmitted : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom InternalTemperatureSensor
]

instance ExternalTemperatureDataTransmitted : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom ExternalTemperatureSensor
]

// C10: Models/Data
instance ThermalDynamicsModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Differential equation-based model simulating heat transfer dynamics within the incubator enclosure, calibrated using real-time sensor data"
    DTDFVocab:inputTo RabbitMQMessageBroker, PythonScipySolver
]

instance AirflowModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Non-linear least squares solver model simulating airflow dynamics and thermal mass effects within the enclosure"
    DTDFVocab:inputTo RabbitMQMessageBroker, PythonScipySolver
]

instance TimeSeriesTemperatureData : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Historical time-series dataset containing temperature measurements from both internal and external sensors for model calibration"
    DTDFVocab:fromData InternalTemperatureDataTransmitted, ExternalTemperatureDataTransmitted
    DTDFVocab:inputTo CalibrationAlgorithm
]

// C11: Enablers
instance RabbitMQMessageBroker : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "RabbitMQ server deployed on Raspberry Pi 4 Model B acting as message broker for asynchronous communication between sensors and DT components"
    DTDFVocab:enables DataIngestionService, ControlSignalDistributionService
]

instance PythonScipySolver : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Python Scipy package implementation for numerical simulations of dynamic behavior including differential equation solving and optimization"
    DTDFVocab:enables ThermalDynamicsModel, AirflowModel, CalibrationAlgorithm
]

instance CalibrationAlgorithm : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Non-linear least squares solver implementation for iterative model parameter adjustment using real-time sensor data"
    DTDFVocab:enables ModelValidationService
]

// C6: Services
instance RealTimeStateEstimationService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Service using sensor data and calibration algorithms to provide best-estimate parameters of the PT's cyber and physical states"
    DTDFVocab:provides TemperatureStateInsight, OperationalBoundsInsight
]

instance ViolationDetectionService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Service implementing violation detection algorithms to assess whether PT operates within safe and optimal bounds"
    DTDFVocab:provides SafetyAlertInsight, PerformanceDeviationInsight
]

instance DynamicSimulationService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Service running differential equation-based models to reproduce and predict PT behavior under current or hypothetical conditions"
    DTDFVocab:provides BehavioralReproductionInsight, ScenarioAnalysisInsight
]

instance ParameterTuningService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Service using optimization algorithms to refine PT models and control strategies for improved efficiency"
    DTDFVocab:provides EfficiencyOptimizationInsight, ResourceAllocationInsight
]

instance SupervisoryControlService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Service employing state estimators and fault detectors to adjust PT operations dynamically via control signals"
    DTDFVocab:provides ControlAdjustmentAction, FaultRecoveryAction
]

// C17: Insights/Actions
instance TemperatureStateInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Real-time temperature state estimation combining sensor data with calibrated model parameters"
]

instance OperationalBoundsInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Continuous assessment of whether current operating conditions remain within predefined safe and optimal ranges"
]

instance SafetyAlertInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Alert generation when detected deviations from safe operational parameters exceed predefined thresholds"
]

instance PerformanceDeviationInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Quantitative analysis of performance deviations from optimal operating conditions with confidence intervals"
]

instance BehavioralReproductionInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Simulation output reproducing the PT's current dynamic behavior based on calibrated models"
]

instance ScenarioAnalysisInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Predictive analysis of potential outcomes under hypothetical operating conditions or parameter changes"
]

instance EfficiencyOptimizationInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Optimized parameter recommendations for improved energy efficiency and reduced operational costs"
]

instance ResourceAllocationInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Recommended adjustments to sensor placement, energy consumption, or maintenance schedules based on predictive models"
]

instance ControlAdjustmentAction : DTDFVocab:Action [
    base:desc "Automated adjustment of heatbed power or fan speed based on real-time state estimation"
    DTDFVocab:IsAutomatic true
]

instance FaultRecoveryAction : DTDFVocab:Action [
    base:desc "Automated corrective actions to restore system to operational bounds following detected faults"
    DTDFVocab:IsAutomatic true
]

// C12: Environment
instance IncubatorEnvironment : DTDFVocab:Environment [
    base:desc "Thermal incubator environment containing all physical components for temperature regulation"
    base:contains StyrofoamEnclosure, HeatbedActuator, AirCirculationFan, InternalTemperatureSensor, ExternalTemperatureSensor
]

// C13: Components
instance StyrofoamEnclosure : DTDFVocab:Component [
    base:desc "Insulated Styrofoam box serving as the primary enclosure for temperature control within the thermal incubator"
    base:isContainedIn IncubatorEnvironment
]

// C14: Data Flow Connections
instance DataIngestionService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Service responsible for receiving and preprocessing sensor data from RabbitMQ message broker"
    DTDFVocab:provides ProcessedTemperatureDataInsight
    DTDFVocab:inputTo RabbitMQMessageBroker
]

instance ProcessedTemperatureDataInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Cleaned and validated temperature data ready for model input after preprocessing"
]

// Additional Data Flow Connections
instance ModelValidationService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Service validating model accuracy through comparison of predicted vs observed behavior"
    DTDFVocab:enables ThermalDynamicsModel, AirflowModel
    DTDFVocab:inputTo PythonScipySolver
]

// Finalizing all connections
instance ControlSignalDistributionService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Service distributing control signals to physical actuators based on supervisory control decisions"
    DTDFVocab:enables HeatbedActuator, AirCirculationFan
    DTDFVocab:inputTo SupervisoryControlService
]

instance virtual_to_physical_interaction : DTDFVocab:VirtualToPhysical [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system transmits control commands to the Physical Twin (PT) via a 'bang-bang controller' for managing the fan and heatbed. Commands are sent through RabbitMQ, with a low-level driver incorporating a 'safe protocol' for execution. Validation mechanisms for commands are not detailed in the documents. Command execution confirmation or feedback systems are not explicitly described. The system does not specify message formats (e.g., binary/text payloads) or conflict resolution mechanisms for concurrent commands."
]

instance twinning_time_scale : DTDFVocab:TimeScale [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system described in the documents operates with temporal synchronization primarily driven by periodic data collection from the Physical Twin (PT) through sensors. Data acquisition occurs 'over time' and is explicitly mentioned as being read 'periodically' by a low-level driver (e.g., temperature data collection). The document does not specify exact synchronization frequencies between the PT and DT, nor does it detail sub-second or millisecond-level updates. Instead, it highlights that accurate models are 'very slow to analyse,' implying that simulation updates or calibration processes may not adhere to strict real-time constraints. No explicit latency requirements for safety-critical systems or temporal granularity needs are provided beyond the periodic sensor readings and the calibration loop involving models, algorithms, and monitors. The system relies on asynchronous communication via RabbitMQ for internal data exchange, but no temporal constraints (e.g., end-to-end latency) are quantified in the provided context."
]

instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system follows a **modular architecture pattern**, where the core components—**data collection**, **models**, **algorithms**, and **monitoring services**—are integrated into a cohesive framework. The system employs **calibration algorithms** to dynamically refine models using real-time PT data, ensuring alignment between the digital and physical representations. Resource management is implicit, relying on the DT's ability to **generate more data and knowledge** through techniques like fault detectors, state estimators, and optimizers. System-wide coordination is achieved via **closed-loop feedback mechanisms**, where monitoring services detect deviations or violations, triggering corrective actions (either automated or human-driven). The DT's orchestration emphasizes **real-time adaptability**, enabling it to simulate, predict, and optimize the PT's behavior under current operating conditions. However, the document does not specify **orchestration protocols**, **containerization frameworks**, or **cloud-edge deployment strategies** for the DT constellation."
]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "The lifecycle of a Digital Twin (DT) as described in the provided documents is primarily framed around the integration of models into a cohesive framework that supports the Physical Twin (PT) throughout its operational phases. The lifecycle begins with the development of abstract representations (e.g., CAD models for geometric properties or dynamic models using differential equations for physical behavior) to understand specific aspects of the system. These models are not discarded post-deployment but are instead integrated into the DT framework, which combines **data** (collected via sensors over time), **models** (knowledge of cyber-physical systems and environmental interactions), and **algorithms** (e.g., calibration, fault detection, state estimation) to enable continuous monitoring and optimization. Transition management between lifecycle phases is implied through the iterative use of calibration algorithms to update models with real-time data, ensuring the DT remains aligned with the PT’s evolving conditions. Lifecycle governance is implicitly supported by the DT’s ability to inform monitors for safety and optimality checks, enabling human or algorithmic intervention when violations occur. However, explicit governance frameworks, such as phase-specific methodologies or formal transition protocols, are not detailed in the document."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "
The Digital Twin system addresses **fidelity and validity** through **calibration algorithms**, specifically a **non-linear least squares solver**, which adjusts model parameters to minimize errors between predicted and observed behavior. The documents reference a **maximum temperature discrepancy of 7 °C** observed during sensor uniformity experiments, indicating a need for model refinement.

No formal **validation and verification methods** (e.g., ISO 16071, Monte Carlo simulations) or **uncertainty quantification** frameworks are described. Error detection and correction mechanisms are limited to **calibration-based adjustments**. Quality assurance processes are not detailed beyond the general integration of models and data in the DT framework.
"
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system utilizes a RabbitMQ server hosted on a Raspberry Pi 4 Model B for message queuing and communication. Data transmission occurs over Wi-Fi for network connectivity and a 1-Wire bus for sensor communication. No explicit details on network topology, bandwidth/latency requirements, redundancy mechanisms, or security protocols are provided in the documents. The system does not mention persistent message queues, star-based topology, or other architectural specifics beyond the RabbitMQ server and 1-Wire/Wi-Fi connections."
]

instance dt_hosting_deployment : DTDFVocab:Deployment [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system is deployed locally on a Raspberry Pi 4 Model B without additional details on hosting platforms (e.g., cloud/edge), computational/storage requirements, or scalability mechanisms. The document does not specify deployment models (e.g., containerized, virtualized) or availability/reliability assurances beyond the local hardware deployment."
]

instance security_and_safety_considerations : DTDFVocab:SecuritySafety [
    base:desc "
The Digital Twin (DT) incorporates **safety monitoring mechanisms** through integrated **monitoring algorithms** that continuously assess the Physical Twin (PT) for safe and optimal performance. The system employs **calibration algorithms** to update models of the Cyber-Physical System (CPS) and its environment, ensuring parameter estimates align with real-time operational conditions. Additionally, the DT includes a **safe protocol** within low-level drivers to enforce operational constraints, mitigating risks during execution. Violations detected by monitors trigger interventions—either automated adjustments or human oversight—to prevent deviations from safe operational boundaries. While no explicit mention of cybersecurity protocols (e.g., encryption, authentication) or formal risk assessment frameworks (e.g., ISO 27001) is provided, the text emphasizes **safety-critical system considerations** via real-time monitoring and adaptive model calibration to preserve system integrity."
]